ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Tetrodotoxin, a very potent toxin, selectively blocks the
voltage-sensitive sodium channels of excitable tissues and neuronal
transmission in skeletal muscles. In humans, paresthesias begin 10-45
minutes after ingestion, usually as tingling of the tongue and inner
surface of the mouth. Other common symptoms include vomiting,
lightheadedness, dizziness, feelings of doom, and weakness. Paralysis
spreads, and death can occur within 6-24 hours, often due to paralysis of
the muscles of respiration. Other signs include salivation, muscle
twitching, diaphoresis, pleuritic chest pain, dysphagia, aphonia, and
convulsions. Severe poisoning is indicated by hypotension, bradycardia,
depressed corneal reflexes, and fixed dilated pupils. There is no specific
antidote and treatment is often supportive.
There are a number of different species of puffer fish or blow fish, each
of which produces a different concentration of the toxin. - Mod.TG]
